			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The classes I have played most in the game are pet classes.  And as irritating as the spam is, sometimes it is simply unavoidable.  The alternative, in some cases, is to allow the pet to do something that could get the party wiped.  Regardless of how proficient pet casters are, there will always be things that are beyond their control that cause situations to occur that will cause spam.
<br />

<br />
With that said, however, here are a few tips that I can offer to pet casters...
<br />

<br />
1) Don't use "/guard here" if you are sitting at a camp and not moving around much.   When the pet is "guarding" he takes a liesurely stroll back to his guard point when you tell him to "/back off".  If he is on "/follow me", however, he will run back to you instead of walking.  
<br />

<br />
2) Always ask for SoW for your pet.  If he runs back to you, but only at his normal speed then the mobs chasing him WILL catch him and cause him to turn around and resume battle.
<br />

<br />
3) Be aware that spam is irritating (even to us pet casters!).  If you MUST spam the "/back off" command, then only do it when it's absolutely necessary.  Sometimes, as Binnen and others have suggested, it is simply better to "/pet go away" and cast a new pet.
<br />

<br />
Tips for non-pet casters (just in case some of you are not aware)...
<br />

<br />
1) Necro pets take 20-30% of their mana to cast a new pet with a 10+ second casting time.  
<br />

<br />
2) Beastlord pets are less effective dealling damage than an un-buffed, un-hasted warrior unless his master buffs him up.  This means that it's more than just re-casting a pet, you also have to spend half a rack of mana (or more) re-buffing them so they can be the big DPSers that groups need.
<br />

<br />
3) Most probably know this, but for completeness...Enchanter pets cannot be controlled.  They are not actually pets.  They are animated shields that agro when their masters get hit by an aggressor.
<br />

<br />
4) Mages are a blend of all of the necro and beastlord extremes.  They require a bit less mana and cast time than a necro, but more than a beastlord.  They require fewer buffs than the beastlord, but more than the necro (think about the summoned items that they use to enhance their pets).
<br />

<br />
So while on the surface it may seem that killing the pet and recasting is a simple matter, often it is not.  There are situations, most certainly, when they can be ditched and recast, but doing so will remove the pet-caster from combat until the pet is back and rebuffed.  
<br />

<br />
Anyway...just my 2 coppers worth.
<br />

<br />
<img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.arach.com/projects/grysm-sig-class2.jpg" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
